   <titles>
      <title>Square Root of 2 is not a Rational Number</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>According to the Theorem of Pythagoras the lengths of the sides of a  right triangle are related by the identity</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>c^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=	</latex>
                     </math>
                     <companion>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Here <math>
                                    <latex>c</latex>
                                 </math> denotes the hypothenuse, i.e. the side opposite to the right angle, of the right triangle. </para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </companion>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>a^2 + b^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>Therefore, in a square of edge length 1, we find for the length of the diagonal</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>c^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>1^2 + 1^2 = 2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>which implies that <math>
                     <latex>c=\sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/Square.png"/>
            </media>
            <para>
               <para.body>Thus, from a geometric point of view, the number <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math> has a natural place in the number system. Yet, it is not the ratio of any two integers. One way to see this is by the following proof by contradiction:</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>The following argument will show that if there were integers <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> such that <math>
                     <latex>a/b = \sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math>, with no common divisor in <math>
                     <latex>a,b</latex>
                  </math>, then <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> would have to be both even. But then <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> have the common divisor <math>
                     <latex>2</latex>
                  </math>, a contradiction, and so the assumption that <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math> is a ratio of two integers must be false.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>To see this argument, let's analyze what happens if there were integers <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> satisfying <math>
                     <latex>a/b = \sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math>. Through cancellation, we can then achieve that <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> have no common divisor. Now we would then have the following observations:</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\dfrac{a}{b}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\dfrac{a^2}{b^2}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>2b^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>a^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>Now if <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> are integers, this means that <math>
                     <latex>a^2</latex>
                  </math> and, hence, <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> is even. So we know that <math>
                     <latex>a=2k</latex>
                  </math> and, hence, <math>
                     <latex>a^2=4k^2</latex>
                  </math>. Substituting in the last identity above, we find,</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>2b^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>4k^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>b^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>2k^2</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>Thus <math>
                     <latex>b^2</latex>
                  </math> and, hence, <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> are even. So we see that <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> have the common divisor <math>
                     <latex>2</latex>
                  </math>, a contradiction to the assumption that <math>
                     <latex>a</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>b</latex>
                  </math> have no common divisor.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Thus we have evidence that there are points on the number line which do not correspond to any ratio of integers. We call such numbers ‘irrational’ for short.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Some reports about the discovery of irrational numbers paint quite a dramatic picture: among historians there is wide agreement that, within the school of Pythagorean philosophers, Hippasus of Metapontum discovered that <math>
                     <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                  </math> was irrational. Up to that point, however, the Pythagoreans believed that every number was a ratio of integers. Hippasus' discovery contradicted this belief, and according to some reports he was punished by being drowned at sea.
				</para.body>
               <index.author>
                  <name>
                     <first> </first>
                     <last>Pythagoras</last>
                  </name>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Pythagoras</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Appears here as the leader of Greek philosophers who believed that every number was a ratio of integers.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.author>
               <index.author>
                  <name>
                     <first> </first>
                     <last>Hippasus of Metapontum</last>
                  </name>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Hippasus of Metapontum</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Appears here as a member of Greek philosophers, the Pythagoreans, who believed that every number was a ratio of integers. Hippasus shattered this belief by showing that <math>
                              <latex>\sqrt{2}</latex>
                           </math> is not a rational number.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.author>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
